Looking at the total amount of construction over the time period covered in the data set, we start to see the data increase towards the beginning of the time range, only to later decrease down to or below original levels. Then the data potentially starts to increase again at the end of the range, however we would need more data points to confirm that. We also see cyclicality in the data that seems consistent over the time range.

Based on this plot, we can conclude that this data seems to exhibit a non-linear trend. We will follow the model presented in Example 2 of the lecture series.

Since we are interested in private versus public construction spending, we would also be interested in viewing construction spending broken out by private and public, so we'll look at that next.

It's interesting to see that most, if not all, of the trend seen in total construction spending is shown in private construction spending. Private construction has consistently been at much higher levels than public construction, and so it makes sense that the overall trend would be more representative of private construction spending in this case.

Public construction spending doesn't clearly exhibit a linear trend either, with maybe slight increases and decreases over the time range (looks like a bow shape).

With all this in mind, we will model both private and public construction with a non-linear trend, as we did in Example 2 of Lecture.

The modeling equation for each data series could be represented as: $H\left(m \right) = T\left( m \right) + C\left( m \right) + \epsilon \left( m \right)$

where

  • $H\left( m \right)$ = Number of homes sold in Month $m$
  • $m$ = the index of the month
  • $T\left( m \right)$ = $T$ represents the trend of the data which, in this case, could be nonlinear. $T\left( m \right)$ is the trend value for Month $m$.
  • $C\left( m \right)$ = Cyclicality demand component which plays an analogous role to seasonality, $S\left( q \right)$, except that the pattern repeats after period whose duration might not be one year.
  • $\epsilon \left( m \right)$ is the portion of demand that we will not be able to fit with $T \left(m \right)$ and $C \left( m \right)$.

We will begin with the private construction data series and decompose the series into its individual components:

Private Construction Spending¶

In [7]:
# Create a function to calculate the squared error for private spending relative to the original data series
def sqErr_Private(row):
    return (row['Private Construction'] - row['MovAvgPrivate'])**2

# As in the lecture, we will create columns to store the moving average of private spending and the squared error computed by the function we just created above
# Keep these columns blank for now, we will update later
df_const['MovAvgPrivate'] = np.NaN
df_const['sqErr_Private'] = np.NaN

# Changing the DataFrame index to DatetimeIndex data type is required for using one of the functions below
df_const.index = pd.date_range(start='1/1/2002', periods = len(df_const['Private Construction']), freq='M')

# Establish a window that will be used to calculate the moving average
# Since there is seasonality in the data, we will do a centered moving average calculation that will use past and future data points in the calculation
windowPrivate = 36
windowPrivate = windowPrivate - windowPrivate % 2

# Calculate the moving average for all possible data points in the series
for i in range(int(windowPrivate/2),df_const.shape[0]-int(windowPrivate/2)):
    df_const.loc[df_const.index[i],'MovAvgPrivate'] = (0.5*df_const.iloc[i - int(windowPrivate/2)]['Private Construction'] + df_const.iloc[i - int(windowPrivate/2)+1:i + int(windowPrivate/2)]['Private Construction'].sum() + 0.5*df_const.iloc[i + int(windowPrivate/2)]['Private Construction'])/float(windowPrivate)

# Apply the squared error function to the dataframe, appending a new column    
df_const['sqErr_Private'] = df_const.apply(sqErr_Private,axis='columns')

# Since there are now N/A's in the data, remove these to get better results
df_const.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)

Now we have created a moving average for private construction spending, as well as a squared error column for each month that compares this moving average to the actual monthly total. We have also removed any rows with "N/A"s.

Next we will visualize the moving average relative to the actual data.

# Create column to calculate the residual of the moving average
df_const['R1Private'] = df_const['Private Construction'] - df_const['MovAvgPrivate']

# Create column to compute the residual calculated above as a percentage of total private construction spending

The remaining residuals seem to be largely driven by cycles within the data, so we will now evaluate that cyclicality.

We will compute autocorrelations to determine how many periods exist in the cyclicality of the data.

In [11]:
maxCorrPrivate = 0.0
periodPrivate = np.NaN
for i in range(1,37):
    corrPrivate = df_const['R1Private'].autocorr(lag=i)
    print('Correlation, lag ',i,'   ',corrPrivate)
    if corrPrivate > maxCorrPrivate:
        maxCorrPrivate = corrPrivate
        periodPrivate = i
print('period = ',periodPrivate,'     Maximum Correlation = ',maxCorrPrivate)

Now we will do the same process for public construction:

Public Construction Spending¶

In [17]:
# Create a function to calculate the squared error for private spending relative to the original data series
def sqErr_Public(row):
    return (row['Public Construction'] - row['MovAvgPublic'])**2

# As in the lecture, we will create columns to store the moving average of private spending and the squared error computed by the function we just created above
# Keep these columns blank for now, we will update later
df_const['MovAvgPublic'] = np.NaN
df_const['sqErr_Public'] = np.NaN

# Establish a window that will be used to calculate the moving average
# Since there is seasonality in the data, we will do a centered moving average calculation that will use past and future data points in the calculation
windowPublic = 36
windowPublic = windowPublic - windowPublic % 2

# Calculate the moving average for all possible data points in the series
for i in range(int(windowPublic/2),df_const.shape[0]-int(windowPublic/2)):
    df_const.loc[df_const.index[i],'MovAvgPublic'] = (0.5*df_const.iloc[i - int(windowPublic/2)]['Public Construction'] + df_const.iloc[i - int(windowPublic/2)+1:i + int(windowPublic/2)]['Public Construction'].sum() + 0.5*df_const.iloc[i + int(windowPublic/2)]['Public Construction'])/float(windowPublic)

# Apply the squared error function to the dataframe, appending a new column    
df_const['sqErr_Public'] = df_const.apply(sqErr_Public,axis='columns')

# Since there are now N/A's in the data, remove these to get better results
df_const.dropna(how='any',inplace=True)

Now we have created a moving average for public construction spending, as well as a squared error column for each month that compares this moving average to the actual monthly total. We have also removed any rows with "N/A"s.
